set host names in the file below and verify:
$ cat >> /etc/hosts
192.168.1.11      db
192.168.1.11      www.google.com

so all the commands below are connecting to the same host
$ ping db
$ ssh db
$ curl http://www.google.com

if run the command below on the host:
$ hostname
host-2            //it's the actual host name, but other hosts who want to connect to this host dont care the actual name, they read the host name from /etc/hosts without judging the truth.

DNS server:
stores all the host names and matching IP addresses instead of /etc/hosts file
config the IP address of DNS server in this file /etc/resol.conf
$ cat /etc/resolv.conf
nameserver     192.168.1.100

if one IP address is set in /etc/hosts file with a host name AA and mapped another host name BB in DNS server, the system will read from the file /etc/hosts first. 
But this order can be changed, people can make it read from DNS server first followed by /etc/hosts, the file to change this order is /etc/nsswitch.conf:
$ cat /etc/nsswitch.conf
hosts:   files dns

if ping a server that is not on either list, say www.facebook.com
either:
$ cat >> /etc/resolv.conf
nameserver     192.168.1.100
nameserver     8.8.8.8
or in DNS server:
Forward All to 8.8.8.8

why sometimes urls are different when connecting internally and externally of the company:
say, if in DNS server it's set like this:
192.168.1.10        web.mycompany.com
192.168.1.11        db.mycompany.com
192.168.1.12        nfs.mycompany.com
add one more line to the file below:
$ cat >> /etc/resolv.conf
nameserver     192.168.1.100
search         mycompany.com           //this line added
internally and externally ping a server would be different:
$ ping web                   //internally
$ ping web.mycompany.com     //externally


networking basics:
switch is used in the same network for different hosts communicating with each other; router is used among networks.
within a network:
$ ip link                                                //to see interfaces for the host which would be used to connect to the switch 192.168.1.0
eth0: blabla
$ ip addr add 192.168.1.10/24 dev eth0                   //assign ip address on the same network
$ ip addr add 192.168.1.11/24 dev eth0
$ ping 192.168.1.11                                      //the computers can now communicate with each other through the switch

$ route      //prints routing table
$ ip route add 192.168.2.0/24 via 192.168.1.1            //config from 192.168.1.1
$ ip route add 192.168.1.0/24 via 192.168.2.1            //config from 192.168.2.1
$ ip route add 0.0.0.0 via 192.168.2.1                   //config access to all the other networks






